# Instructions

During your interaction with the user, if you find anything reusable in this project (e.g. version of a library, model name), especially about a fix to a mistake you made or a correction you received, you should take note in the `Lessons` section in the `.cursorrules` file so you will not make the same mistake again. 

You should also use the `.cursorrules` file as a Scratchpad to organize your thoughts. Especially when you receive a new task, you should first review the content of the Scratchpad, clear old different task if necessary, first explain the task, and plan the steps you need to take to complete the task. You can use todo markers to indicate the progress, e.g.
[X] Task 1
[ ] Task 2

Also update the progress of the task in the Scratchpad when you finish a subtask.
Especially when you finished a milestone, it will help to improve your depth of task accomplishment to use the Scratchpad to reflect and plan.
The goal is to help you maintain a big picture as well as the progress of the task. Always refer to the Scratchpad when you plan the next step.

# Project Structure

## Authentication & User Role Hierarchy
The platform implements a three-tier authentication system:
1. **Master Admin** (platform owner) - role: 'master_admin'
   - Full access to all organizations and data
   - Can create and manage Sub Admin accounts
   - Access to platform-level analytics and billing
   
2. **Sub Admin** (organization owner) - role: 'sub_admin'
   - Manages only their organization's data
   - Can create and manage Staff users
   - Cannot access other organizations' data
   
3. **Staff** (team members) - role: 'staff'
   - Limited access within their organization
   - Permissions set by Sub Admin
   - Cannot invite other users

Data isolation is enforced through organization_id on all resource tables (facilities, buildings, fields) with Row Level Security (RLS) policies. Master admins bypass organization checks, while others are filtered by their organization_id.

## Data Hierarchy
The application follows a strict hierarchical structure:
1. **Facility** (top level)
   - Contains basic facility information (name, address, type, status, etc.)
   - Has many Buildings
   
2. **Building** (belongs to a Facility)
   - Each building must have a facility_id
   - Contains building information (name, type, square footage, etc.)
   - Has many Rooms
   - Has many Building Systems
   - Has many Renovations
   
3. **Room** (belongs to a Building)
   - Each room must have a building_id
   - Contains room information (number, function, square footage, capacity, etc.)

## URL Structure
The URL structure reflects the data hierarchy:
- `/facilities` - List all facilities
- `/facility/[facilityId]` - View facility details and its buildings
- `/facility/[facilityId]/buildings/new` - Add new building to facility
- `/facility/[facilityId]/buildings/[buildingId]` - View building details and its rooms
- `/facility/[facilityId]/buildings/[buildingId]/rooms/new` - Add new room to building

# Tools

Note all the tools are in python3. So in the case you need to do batch processing, you can always consult the python files and write your own script.

## Screenshot Verification

The screenshot verification workflow allows you to capture screenshots of web pages and verify their appearance using LLMs. The following tools are available:

1. Screenshot Capture:
```bash
venv/bin/python3 tools/screenshot_utils.py URL [--output OUTPUT] [--width WIDTH] [--height HEIGHT]
```

2. LLM Verification with Images:
```bash
venv/bin/python3 tools/llm_api.py --prompt "Your verification question" --provider anthropic --image path/to/screenshot.png
```

Example workflow:
```python
from screenshot_utils import take_screenshot_sync
from llm_api import query_llm

# Take a screenshot

screenshot_path = take_screenshot_sync('https://example.com', 'screenshot.png')

# Verify with LLM

response = query_llm(
    "What is the background color and title of this webpage?",
    provider="anthropic",
    image_path=screenshot_path
)
print(response)
```

## LLM

You always have an LLM at your side to help you with the task. For simple tasks, you could invoke the LLM by running the following command:
```
venv/bin/python3 ./tools/llm_api.py --prompt "What is the capital of France?" --provider "anthropic"
```

The LLM API supports multiple providers:
- Anthropic (default, model: claude-3-sonnet-20240229)
- DeepSeek (model: deepseek-chat)
- Gemini (model: gemini-pro)
- Local LLM (model: Qwen/Qwen2.5-32B-Instruct-AWQ)

But usually it's a better idea to check the content of the file and use the APIs in the `tools/llm_api.py` file to invoke the LLM if needed.

## Web browser

You could use the `tools/web_scraper.py` file to scrape the web.
```bash
venv/bin/python3 ./tools/web_scraper.py --max-concurrent 3 URL1 URL2 URL3
```
This will output the content of the web pages.

## Search engine

You could use the `tools/search_engine.py` file to search the web.
```bash
venv/bin/python3 ./tools/search_engine.py "your search keywords"
```
This will output the search results in the following format:
```
URL: https://example.com
Title: This is the title of the search result
Snippet: This is a snippet of the search result
```
If needed, you can further use the `web_scraper.py` file to scrape the web page content.

# Lessons

## User Specified Lessons

- You have a python venv in ./venv. Always use (activate) it when doing python development. First, to check whether 'uv' is available, use `which uv`. If that's the case, first activate the venv, and then use `uv pip install` to install packages. Otherwise, fall back to `pip`.
- Due to Cursor's limit, when you use `git` and `gh` and need to submit a multiline commit message, first write the message in a file, and then use `git commit -F <filename>` or similar command to commit. And then remove the file. Include "[Cursor] " in the commit message and PR title.

## Cursor learned

- Issue report submission fix: When createIssueReport server action is stuck, ensure: 1) Use await for createServerSupabaseClient(), 2) Wrap RPC calls like log_issue_activity in try-catch blocks as they may not exist, 3) Wrap notification functions in try-catch to prevent submission failure, 4) Issue reports should be fetched along with maintenance tasks and converted to task format for display. Added email notifications alongside SMS for building managers using HTML templates.

- Server action Supabase client best practice: Always use the centralized Supabase client creation functions from `@/lib/supabase/server` (getServiceRoleClient, createServerSupabaseClient) for server actions. Never create custom implementations that return null when env vars are missing. The centralized functions properly handle Next.js server-side environment variable loading and throw descriptive errors. This prevents "Failed to fetch" errors caused by "Supabase client not initialized" in server actions.
- Room database column naming: The rooms table uses 'room_number' as the column name, not 'number'. When querying room data in Supabase queries or accessing room properties in TypeScript, always use 'room_number'. Common error: "column rooms_1.number does not exist" indicates incorrect column reference.

- Hydration error fix: To prevent "Hydration failed because the server rendered HTML didn't match the client" errors, ensure server and client render same initial state. AuthContext starts with user=null and loading=true on both server and client, then loads cached user from localStorage only after hydration using useEffect. Sidebar uses consistent initial logoHref="/" and updates it after component mounts based on user state. This prevents mismatches where server renders href="/" but client renders href="/facilities-map" when cached user exists.
- Sidebar loading optimization: AuthContext implements user data caching in localStorage ('facilitycore_user' key). Cached user is loaded after hydration to show navigation immediately while refreshing data from Supabase in background. Sign-in uses window.location.href for full page reload to ensure proper auth state initialization.
- Logo navigation fix: The Sidebar logo uses a state variable for href that starts with "/" and updates to "/facilities-map" or "/" based on user authentication after hydration. This prevents hydration mismatches while maintaining correct navigation behavior.

- For search results, ensure proper handling of different character encodings (UTF-8) for international queries
- When using seaborn styles in matplotlib, use 'seaborn-v0_8' instead of 'seaborn' as the style name due to recent seaborn version changes

- When searching for recent news, use the current year (2025) instead of previous years, or simply use the "recent" keyword to get the latest information
- Safari has stricter cookie handling than Chrome. For Supabase authentication in Safari:
  - Use localStorage as a fallback for cookie storage
  - Avoid `sameSite: 'lax'` with `secure: false` in development
  - Add longer delays for Safari redirects after authentication
  - Use `window.location.replace()` instead of `window.location.href` for Safari
  - Implement proper auth storage adapters for cross-browser compatibility
- Building creation should use server actions (createBuilding) instead of BuildingService for consistency with the mock data approach
- The Building type in TypeScript doesn't include rooms by default - use extended types when needed
- Safari has stricter cookie handling than Chrome. For Supabase authentication in Safari:
  - Use localStorage as a fallback for cookie storage
  - Avoid `sameSite: 'lax'` with `secure: false` in development
  - Add longer delays for Safari redirects after authentication
  - Use `window.location.replace()` instead of `window.location.href` for Safari
  - Implement proper auth storage adapters for cross-browser compatibility
- Select dropdown text color issue: When using SelectValue components, avoid adding `className="text-gray-400"` as it overrides the white text color from SelectTrigger. The SelectValue should inherit the white text color from the trigger, and placeholders should be styled through the SelectTrigger's `data-[placeholder]:text-gray-400` class.
- Supabase auth helpers migration: The `@supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs` package is deprecated and causes build errors. Always use `@supabase/ssr` for new projects, or `@supabase/supabase-js` with service role client for API routes. The service role client approach bypasses authentication complexity and works well for API routes in development.
- PDF viewer reliability: CDN-based PDF viewers (like PDF.js Express) can fail due to network issues. Always provide a reliable fallback using iframe-based viewers that leverage the browser's built-in PDF capabilities. Use CDN-based enhanced viewers as optional features, not primary functionality.
- Room capacity calculation: Implemented automatic capacity calculation based on California Building Code (CBC) requirements. The calculation uses standardized occupancy factors (sq ft per person) for different room types. Features include: automatic calculation when room function or square footage changes, manual override capability, visual indicators for calculated vs manual values, and CBC compliance information display. The calculator is in `src/utils/capacityCalculator.ts`.
- Room occupancy terminology: Updated all room capacity references to use "Occupancy" terminology for consistency with building code standards. Both AddRoomModal and EditRoomModal now use occupancy fields that automatically calculate based on room type and square footage. The calculation is triggered immediately when both room function and square footage are entered.
- Server action Supabase client best practice: Always use the centralized Supabase client creation functions from `@/lib/supabase/server` (getServiceRoleClient, createServerSupabaseClient) for server actions. Never create custom implementations that return null when env vars are missing. The centralized functions properly handle Next.js server-side environment variable loading and throw descriptive errors. This prevents "Failed to fetch" errors caused by "Supabase client not initialized" in server actions.
- Theme system implementation: When implementing light/dark mode themes, always use semantic CSS variables instead of hardcoded colors. This allows for automatic theme switching without component updates. Key variables include: `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `text-muted-foreground`, `bg-card`, `border-border`, `bg-primary`, `text-primary`, `hover:bg-accent`. All interactive elements should use theme-aware hover states and proper contrast ratios for accessibility.
- Pipedrive-inspired light theme: The application now uses a clean, professional light theme inspired by Pipedrive's UI design. Key characteristics: 1) White backgrounds (#ffffff) with light gray sections (#f9fafb), 2) Blue primary color (#007aff) for buttons and links, 3) Green accent color (#00b16a) for success states, 4) Dark gray text (#1f2937) for high contrast, 5) Light gray borders (#e5e7eb), 6) Subtle shadows and rounded corners (6px), 7) Professional sans-serif font stack, 8) Clean minimalist design with good spacing. The theme is implemented using next-themes for reliable theme switching.
- Field edit modal enhancements: When improving modal UX, implement sticky headers and action buttons for better scrolling experience. Use `bg-card/95 backdrop-blur-sm` for sticky elements to maintain context while scrolling. Enhance card styling with subtle shadows (`shadow-sm hover:shadow-md`) and smooth transitions (`transition-all duration-200`). Improve visual hierarchy with semibold headings, consistent icon usage, and proper spacing (`pb-3 mb-6`). Use enhanced button styling with gradient backgrounds and shadow effects (`shadow-lg hover:shadow-xl`) for professional polish.
- Avoid hardcoded theme colors: Never use hardcoded colors like `bg-gray-900`, `text-white`, `border-gray-700` etc. in components as they break light mode support. Always use semantic CSS variables: `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `bg-card`, `text-card-foreground`, `border-border`, `text-muted-foreground`, `bg-input`, `text-primary`, `bg-primary`, etc. This ensures components work seamlessly in both light and dark themes without requiring theme-specific conditional styling.
- Field image upload fix: The updateField function was failing to save uploaded images because it was trying to save File objects directly to the database. Fixed by updating updateField() to: 1) Extract image-related data (field_images, existing_image_urls) before database update, 2) Upload new images to Supabase Storage first, 3) Combine existing and new image URLs, 4) Update the field with image URLs in a separate database call. This ensures image uploads work properly when editing existing fields, with proper error handling and fallback to existing data if image operations fail.
- Avoid hardcoded theme colors: Never use hardcoded colors like `bg-gray-900`, `text-white`, `border-gray-700` etc. in components as they break light mode support. Always use semantic CSS variables: `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `bg-card`, `text-card-foreground`, `border-border`, `text-muted-foreground`, `bg-input`, `text-primary`, `bg-primary`, etc. This ensures components work seamlessly in both light and dark themes without requiring theme-specific conditional styling.
- Supabase chunkedCookie.startsWith error fix: The "chunkedCookie.startsWith is not a function" error occurs when Supabase's cookie handling receives non-string values. Fixed by simplifying the custom cookie handling in `src/lib/supabase/client.ts`: 1) Remove complex base64 encoding/decoding logic that was causing type issues, 2) Always return strings from cookie.get() method (null for missing cookies), 3) Simplify cookie parsing to use standard decodeURIComponent without JSON parsing, 4) Fix SameSite handling for localhost/HTTPS contexts, 5) Remove localStorage fallback from cookie operations to prevent interference. Key principle: Keep cookie handling simple and always return string values to prevent Supabase internal chunking errors.
- Reservation authentication requirement: Implemented authentication checks for all reservation submission forms to ensure users are signed in before completing reservations. Key implementation: 1) Added `useUser()` hook to reservation components (FieldReservationModal, FacilityRentalModal, FieldDetailModal), 2) Check authentication status before submission with `if (!user && !userLoading)` condition, 3) Show dedicated auth-required step/modal with reservation summary, sign-up/sign-in buttons, and option to continue editing, 4) Pre-fill forms with user data when authenticated (name, email, phone, organization based on user type), 5) Professional auth modal styling with gradient backgrounds, proper spacing, and clear call-to-action buttons, 6) Maintain reservation data when users navigate to sign-in/sign-up pages. This ensures all facility and field reservations require user accounts while providing smooth UX for both new and existing users.
- Policy acknowledgment Yes/No buttons: Replaced all policy acknowledgment checkboxes with Yes/No buttons for better user experience and clarity. Implementation: 1) Changed boolean state variables to string values ('yes'/'no'), 2) Used Button components with conditional styling (green for Yes, red for No), 3) Updated validation logic to check for 'yes' values instead of true, 4) Applied to all reservation forms (FacilityRentalModal, FieldReservationModal, FieldDetailModal), 5) Maintained visual hierarchy with policy text followed by button pair, 6) Submit button remains disabled until all policies are acknowledged with 'Yes'. This provides clearer user interaction compared to traditional checkboxes.
- Authentication hierarchy implementation: Established a clear user hierarchy system: 1) **Master Admin** (formerly district_approver) - Highest level, can invite sub-master admins and have full system access, 2) **Sub-Master Admin** (formerly site_approver) - Can invite/create facility staff, managers, coordinators for their facilities, 3) **Staff/Manager/Coordinator** - Created through invitation only by master or sub-master admins, 4) **Renters** - Public users who sign up through the landing page to book facilities. Key features: Created user_invitations table with token-based invitation system, invitation acceptance page at /auth/accept-invitation, InviteUserModal component for sending invitations, role-based permissions for who can invite whom, automatic role mapping for backward compatibility. The system ensures proper access control with master_admin (85baris@gmail.com) at the top of the hierarchy.
- Sidebar navigation role checking: When implementing new authentication hierarchies, always update all components that check user roles. The sidebar navigation was checking for an old 'admin' role that doesn't exist in the new user_role enum. Updated to check for 'master_admin', 'sub_master', and legacy roles ('district_approver', 'site_approver') for backward compatibility. Key principle: When changing role systems, search for all role checks throughout the codebase and update them to match the new enum values.
- Landing page signup fix: Fixed the "Try For Free" button on the landing page that was incorrectly linking to `/auth/sign-in` instead of `/auth/sign-up`. Also identified that signup failures are typically due to missing Supabase environment variables. Created comprehensive setup guide (SUPABASE_SETUP.md) with step-by-step instructions for configuring Supabase credentials, applying database migrations, and troubleshooting common signup issues. Key issue: Projects need `.env.local` file with NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL, NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, and SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY to function properly.
- Landing page animation fix: Fixed missing animation error by removing reference to deleted `anim1.json` file. The hero section now uses `managerAnimationData` instead, which is appropriate for facility management software. Available animations in `/public/animations/lottie/`: manager.json, docs.json, Pen.json, virtualT.json.
- App layout ChatAssistant fix: Removed references to ChatAssistant component in (app)/layout.tsx that was causing compilation errors after cleanup. The chat functionality was removed during cleanup but the layout still had imports and component usage that needed to be removed.
- Email verification workflow: Fixed the "Invalid login credentials" error that occurs when users try to sign in before verifying their email. Key improvements: 1) Updated signup flow to check if email verification is required (no session returned), 2) Created dedicated /auth/verify-email page with resend functionality and helpful instructions, 3) Updated auth callback to create user records after email verification, 4) Enhanced sign-in error handling to detect unverified emails and redirect to verification page, 5) Improved user messaging throughout the verification process. The flow now properly handles Supabase's email confirmation requirement: signup → email verification → callback creates user record → redirect to facilities map.
- Sign-in redirect fix: Fixed sign-in redirect loop by using window.location.href instead of router.push for authentication redirects. Key changes: 1) Updated sign-in page to use window.location.href for full page reload after successful authentication to ensure auth state is properly picked up, 2) Added 500ms delay after sign-in to allow session to be established, 3) Improved session checking in protected pages with proper getSession() calls before getUser(), 4) Added auth state change listeners to handle session changes properly. This ensures the authentication state is fully loaded before navigation occurs.
- Sign-out functionality fix: Fixed sign-out issues by using window.location.href instead of router.push for authentication redirects. Applied to both TopBar.tsx and Sidebar.tsx components. Key improvements: 1) Added proper error handling with try-catch blocks, 2) Used window.location.href for full page reload to ensure auth state is completely cleared, 3) Added setTimeout delays to allow session cleanup before redirect, 4) Enhanced user feedback with toast notifications in Sidebar, 5) Ensured redirect happens even if sign-out encounters errors. This prevents auth state persistence issues that can occur with client-side routing.
- App Router _document conflict: When using Next.js App Router, remove any `_document.tsx` files from the `src/pages/` directory as they conflict with the new routing system. The error "Cannot find module '_document.js'" indicates this conflict. App Router uses different mechanisms for document customization through layout.tsx files. Remove the entire `src/pages/` directory when fully migrated to App Router to prevent conflicts.
- Staff assignment system missing database tables: The user attempted to assign staff to rooms and fields but functionality wasn't working. Root cause: The database migration for staff assignment tables (`staff_field_assignments`, `staff_room_assignments`, `room_blockout_dates`) was never applied. Solution: Created setup guide (STAFF_ASSIGNMENTS_SETUP.md) and verification script (scripts/check-staff-assignments.js). The migration file exists at `supabase/migrations/20250124_staff_field_room_assignments.sql` and must be manually applied via Supabase SQL Editor. The UI components and server actions are properly implemented - only missing the database schema. Once migration is applied, users can assign staff to rooms/fields enabling collaborative calendar management where multiple users can see each other's events.
- Staff assignment foreign key mismatch: After creating staff assignment tables, assignments still failed with foreign key constraint errors. Root cause: The migration created foreign key constraints referencing `auth.users(id)` but the application uses a custom `users` table. Solution: Drop existing FK constraints and recreate them pointing to the `users` table instead. Also disable RLS temporarily for testing. This is a common issue when mixing Supabase auth with custom user tables.
- Field information modal null property errors: The FieldDetailModal component was throwing errors when field properties were null/undefined. Fixed by adding proper null checks for `field.parking_spots`, `field.surface_type`, and ensuring `field.gallery_images` is an array before using array methods. Always add null safety checks when accessing nested object properties in React components.
- Staff assignment UI not updating after assignment: Staff assignments were working in the database but the UI wasn't updating. Fixed by: 1) Adding `onClose()` call after successful assignment in AssignStaffToFieldModal, 2) Adding `loadFields()` call in the onAssignmentChange callback to refresh field data, 3) Adding success toast notification. Always ensure modals close and parent data refreshes after successful operations.
- Server action authentication failing: Server actions using Supabase need proper cookie handling for authentication. The createClient function in src/lib/supabase/server.ts was not handling cookies, causing auth.getUser() to fail. Fix: Import and use `createServerSupabaseClient` which properly handles Next.js cookies for authentication. This is a common issue when server actions get "User not authenticated" errors despite the user being logged in.
- Server actions cannot be called from client components: Server actions with 'use server' directive cannot be called directly from client components with 'use client'. This causes 500 Internal Server Errors. Solution: Create API routes (e.g., /api/users/available) to handle the logic and call the API from client components using fetch(). Convert server action logic to API route using createServerSupabaseClient for authentication. This separation ensures proper server-client architecture in Next.js App Router.
- Favicon 500 error fix: Having favicon.ico files in both /public/ and /src/app/ directories causes routing conflicts in Next.js App Router. The recommended approach for Next.js 13+ is to have favicon.ico only in the /src/app/ directory. Remove duplicate from /public/ to resolve 500 Internal Server Error when loading favicon. Next.js App Router treats favicon.ico in the app directory as a special route.
- Multiple Supabase client instances fix: The warning "Multiple GoTrueClient instances detected in the same browser context" occurs when multiple Supabase client instances are created. This was caused by a legacy src/lib/supabase.ts file creating a global client instance while the modern SSR setup uses src/lib/supabase/client.ts and src/lib/supabase/server.ts. Solution: Remove the legacy supabase.ts file and update all imports to use createClient() from '@/lib/supabase/client' instead of importing the global supabase instance. Each component should call createClient() locally when needed to ensure proper SSR compatibility.
- Next.js console warnings cleanup: Fixed multiple console warnings: 1) Replaced deprecated images.domains with images.remotePatterns in next.config.js for proper image optimization, 2) Added logging configuration to reduce verbose fetch logs, 3) Disabled build activity indicators to reduce console noise, 4) Added optimizePackageImports for better tree shaking, 5) Improved font loading with proper preload and fallback settings, 6) Cleared .next cache to fix vendor chunk module errors. These changes reduce development console noise and improve performance.
- Staff facility assignments database setup: Successfully created `staff_facility_assignments` table with correct foreign key references to custom `users` table instead of `auth.users`. Key steps: 1) Created corrected migration with proper user_id/assigned_by FK constraints pointing to users(id), 2) Applied table creation with indexes and RLS disabled for testing, 3) Created facility assignments for staff user rahimiabdul85@gmail.com to all 4 facilities with standard staff permissions (manage_calendar, create_blockouts, view_reservations, view_reports), 4) Fixed staff_field_assignments FK constraints to also use custom users table. The staff assignment system is now properly configured with the user able to see facilities they're assigned to and the staff dashboard should work without relationship errors.
- Modern UI transformation using shadcn/ui: Completed comprehensive UI modernization instead of purchasing Tailwind CSS Plus. Key improvements: 1) Enhanced Tailwind config with modern color system, animations, and design tokens, 2) Cleaned up global CSS with Linear/Vercel-inspired light theme, 3) Created enhanced Button component with gradient, hover-lift, and interactive variants, 4) Developed modern Card component with interactive states, 5) Added professional animations (fade-in, slide-up, gentle-bounce), 6) Implemented better shadows (soft, medium, strong, glow), 7) Enhanced typography with Inter font and improved spacing, 8) Created modern utility classes (hover-lift, card-modern, btn-primary), 9) Added accessibility features (reduced motion, high contrast), 10) Optimized for performance with minimal bundle impact. The transformation provides a professional, modern interface that rivals top SaaS applications without recurring costs.
- Browser extension hydration errors: Fixed hydration errors caused by browser extensions (like LastPass) injecting DOM elements that don't match server-rendered HTML. Solution: 1) Added `suppressHydrationWarning` to both `<html>` and `<body>` elements in root layout.tsx, 2) Created `NoSSR` component to handle client-side only rendering, 3) Created `AuthLoadingSkeleton` component as fallback during hydration, 4) Wrapped auth pages (SignInForm, SignUpForm) with NoSSR to prevent hydration mismatches, 5) Split auth page components into separate form components wrapped by NoSSR export. This pattern prevents "data-lastpass-icon-root" and similar extension-injected elements from causing hydration failures. The approach maintains SSR benefits while handling browser extension interference gracefully.
- Math.random() hydration error fix: Fixed hydration errors caused by using Math.random() in server-side rendering. The issue occurs when Math.random() generates different values on server vs client, causing HTML mismatch. In the landing page, amenities arrays were using Math.random() to slice different numbers of amenities: `amenities: ['WiFi', 'Parking'].slice(0, Math.floor(Math.random() * 4) + 1)`. Solution: Remove Math.random() calls and use consistent data between server and client. Instead of random slicing, use the full arrays: `amenities: ['WiFi', 'Parking', 'Climate Control', 'Security']`. This ensures identical rendering on both server and client, preventing hydration mismatches. Rule: Never use Date.now(), Math.random(), or other time-based/random values in SSR components unless properly handled with suppressHydrationWarning or client-side only rendering.
- Environment variables not loading in Next.js: When getting "supabaseUrl is required" errors despite having .env.local file with correct variables, the issue is often that Next.js isn't properly loading environment variables on server restart. Solution: 1) Add proper error handling to all Supabase client creation functions instead of using non-null assertions (!), 2) Validate environment variables exist before passing to Supabase client constructors, 3) Restart the Next.js development server to properly load .env.local file, 4) Use descriptive error messages that clearly indicate which environment variables are missing. This pattern prevents cryptic Supabase internal errors and makes debugging environment issues much easier. Always validate env vars in server-side functions that create Supabase clients.
- Server action Supabase client mismatch: When server actions show "supabaseUrl is required" errors even with environment variables set, check if the action is calling `createClient()` from `@supabase/supabase-js` without parameters instead of using the proper server-side client. Server actions must use `createServerSupabaseClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server` which handles authentication cookies correctly. The raw `createClient()` from Supabase requires URL and key parameters. This is a common issue in Next.js App Router when mixing different Supabase client creation patterns. Always use the server-specific client for server actions to ensure proper authentication handling.
- Field creation missing database columns: When getting "Could not find the 'city' column of 'fields' in the schema cache" errors during field creation, the issue is that the fields table is missing address columns that the application expects. The fields migration may have been partially applied or some columns weren't created. Solution: 1) Check which columns exist in the fields table using scripts/check-fields-schema.js, 2) Apply the address fields migration manually via Supabase SQL Editor using scripts/fix-fields-columns.sql, 3) Verify the missing columns (city, state, full_address, street_address, zip_code) are added, 4) Also check for other potential missing columns like aerial_image_url, possible_uses. The issue occurs when database migrations aren't fully applied or when the application code expects columns that don't exist in the database schema.
- Modal closing after field creation: Fixed issue where AddFieldModal wouldn't close after successful field creation. Solution: 1) Parent component (FacilityFields) now handles modal closing by calling setIsCreateModalOpen(false) on success, 2) AddFieldModal no longer tries to close itself - it just handles form submission and lets parent control modal state, 3) This pattern prevents issues where thrown errors would stop modal from closing, 4) Similar pattern used in CreateBlockoutModal where parent handles modal state through onSuccess callback. Key principle: Let parent components control modal open/close state for better error handling.
- Field calendar blockout permissions: Master admins and district_approvers should have full permissions to create/delete field blockouts without needing staff_field_assignments. Fixed by updating createBlockout and deleteBlockout functions in staff.ts to check user role first. If user is master_admin or district_approver, skip permission checks. Otherwise, check staff_field_assignments for create_blockouts permission. This ensures master admins can manage all field blockouts while regular staff need specific assignments.
- FormData field name consistency: When forms send FormData to server actions, the field names must match exactly. Common issue: HTML forms using camelCase names (e.g., `name="buildingType"`) while server actions expect snake_case (e.g., `formData.get('building_type')`). This causes "Missing required fields" errors even when all fields are filled. Solution: Always use snake_case field names in forms to match database column names. Check all FormData.get() calls in server actions to ensure consistency. Fixed building creation by changing buildingType→building_type, squareFootage→square_footage, etc.
- Modal closing after successful creation: When creation modals don't close after successful submission, the issue is usually that post-creation operations (like router.refresh(), loadFields(), etc.) are failing and preventing the success callback from completing. Solution: Close the modal immediately after successful database operation, before any other operations. Pattern: 1) await createItem(data), 2) onClose() or setModalOpen(false), 3) try/catch around secondary operations like refresh/reload. This ensures the modal closes even if background operations fail. Pattern used in AddRoomModal and AddFieldModal - close first, then handle background updates.
- Dialog component onOpenChange fix: The shadcn/ui Dialog component's `onOpenChange` prop expects a function that receives a boolean parameter (true when opening, false when closing). When modals have cancel/close buttons that don't work, check if the Dialog is using `onOpenChange={onClose}` directly. This fails because onClose doesn't handle the boolean parameter. Fix: Use `onOpenChange={(open) => !open && onClose()}` which only calls onClose when the dialog is closing (open is false). This ensures the X button, Escape key, and backdrop clicks all properly close the modal. Applied to AddRoomModal, EditBuildingModal, AddFieldModal, EditRoomModal, EditFieldModal, AddSystemModal, AddRenovationModal, and many other modals for consistency.
- Renter creation security restriction: Implemented security measures to prevent master admins from creating renter accounts through the admin interface. Changes: 1) Removed 'renter' option from AddUserModal role selection dropdown, 2) Removed all renter-specific form fields and validation logic from AddUserModal, 3) Added server-side validation in createUser() action to reject attempts to create renter accounts with clear error message, 4) Database-level restrictions already existed via can_invite_user() function and InviteUserModal correctly excludes renters. This ensures renters can only sign up themselves through the public registration flow, preventing admins from assigning passwords to renter accounts. Security principle: User account creation should follow proper authentication flows and role-based restrictions.
- Re-enabled renter creation for testing: Temporarily removed the security restriction preventing admin creation of renter accounts to allow testing of permission levels and user access. Changes: 1) Removed server-side validation in createUser() action that blocked renter creation, 2) Updated People page to show "Add Renter" button instead of toast message, 3) AddUserModal already supported renter creation with organization selection. This enables admins to create test renter accounts to verify permission levels and access restrictions. Consider re-implementing security measures after testing phase is complete.
- Renter invitation system implementation: Implemented secure invitation-based renter creation system extending existing invitation infrastructure. Key components: 1) Updated database function can_invite_user() to allow master_admin to invite renters, 2) Extended InviteUserModal with renter role, phone field, and organization selection, 3) Modified createUser() action to send invitations for renters instead of direct creation, 4) Enhanced invitation acceptance flow to handle renter organization assignment, 5) Added email notification system with console logging ready for email service integration, 6) Updated AddUserModal to show invitation sent message for renters. Security benefits: renters control passwords, email verification required, time-limited tokens (7 days), audit trail with invited_by tracking, organization assignment maintained. Testing flow: People page → Renter tab → Add Renter → Fill details → Send Invitation → Renter receives email → Clicks link → Sets password → Account created with proper permissions.
- Email service error handling: When initializing email services like SendGrid, never throw errors at the module level as it crashes any page that imports the module. Instead, check for configuration at runtime and gracefully fall back to console logging when email services aren't configured. This prevents "SENDGRID_API_KEY is not set" crashes and allows development without email configuration. Always use a boolean flag (like `sendGridConfigured`) to track if the service is available and handle accordingly in email-sending functions.
- SelectItem empty value error: Never use empty string values (`value=""`) in SelectItem components as newer versions of shadcn/ui Select require non-empty values. Use meaningful values like "none", "unassigned", or "default" instead. Update form submission logic to handle these special values by converting them to null/undefined when needed. This prevents "A <Select.Item /> must have a value prop that is not an empty string" errors.
- Facility photos table missing error: The facility photos tab shows PostgreSQL error "42P01" (undefined_table) when the `facility_photos` table doesn't exist in the database. The migration file exists at `supabase/migrations/20250115_create_facility_photos_table.sql` but hasn't been applied. Solution: 1) Go to Supabase project dashboard, 2) Navigate to SQL Editor, 3) Copy and paste the migration file contents, 4) Execute the SQL to create the table, storage bucket, RLS policies, and indexes. This creates the complete facility photos system with secure photo storage and metadata tracking. The migration creates facility_photos table with columns for photo URLs, storage paths, metadata, and proper foreign key relationships to facilities table.
- Room function dropdown scrolling fix: When dropdowns have many options (20+ room functions), they need proper scrolling configuration. Fixed by: 1) Adding `max-h-[300px] overflow-y-auto` to SelectContent components in AddRoomModal and EditRoomModal, 2) Updating global SelectViewport to include max-height constraint, 3) Adding custom scrollbar styles for select dropdowns in globals.css for better visibility, 4) Ensuring all 20 room functions are included in AddRoomForm component. This allows users to scroll through all options including "Restroom" and "Other" which were previously inaccessible at the bottom of the list. Use mouse wheel, trackpad, arrow keys, or touch scrolling to navigate through all options.
- Server action authentication client mismatch: When server actions show "User not authenticated" errors even with logged-in users, check if the action is using the correct Supabase client. Server actions must use different clients for different purposes: 1) Use `createServerSupabaseClient()` for authentication checks (`auth.getUser()`) as it has access to cookies, 2) Use `getServiceRoleClient()` for database operations to bypass RLS. Never use service role client for auth operations - it doesn't have cookie access and will always fail authentication. Pattern: get user with createServerSupabaseClient, then use getServiceRoleClient for database operations.
- Three-tier authentication system: The platform implements a three-tier hierarchy: 1) Master Admin (platform owner) - full access to all organizations and data, can create Sub Admins, 2) Sub Admin (organization owner) - manages only their organization's data, can invite Staff users, 3) Staff (team members) - limited access within their organization based on permissions. Implementation: user_role enum with values 'master_admin', 'sub_admin', 'staff'. Data isolation enforced through organization_id on all resource tables with RLS policies. Master admins bypass org checks, others filtered by organization_id. Legacy roles mapped: district_approver→master_admin, site_approver/manager/coordinator→sub_admin, others→staff. Migration at supabase/migrations/20250131_three_tier_authentication.sql.
- Supabase email template customization: Created branded HTML email templates for Facilitycore to replace plain text emails. Templates use table-based layout for email client compatibility, feature professional styling with blue gradient header (#007aff to #0051cc), and include both confirmation and password reset emails. To implement: 1) Go to Supabase Dashboard → Authentication → Email Templates, 2) Update subjects and paste HTML from email-templates/*.html files, 3) Templates use Supabase variables like {{ .ConfirmationURL }}, 4) For production, configure custom SMTP (SendGrid, Mailgun, etc.) for better deliverability. Key files: email-templates/confirm-signup.html, reset-password.html, user-invitation.html. Quick start guide in SUPABASE_EMAIL_QUICK_START.md.
- Supabase function replacement errors: When dropping and recreating PostgreSQL functions, several issues can occur: 1) Function signature mismatch - DROP statement must match exact parameter types, 2) Dependencies - Use CASCADE to handle dependent objects, 3) Type conflicts - user_role enum vs text mismatch. Solution: Use `DROP FUNCTION IF EXISTS function_name CASCADE` to handle all dependencies. For flexible parameter handling, use text type instead of enums and cast when needed. Check existing functions with pg_proc queries before dropping. Always use `SET search_path = public` in function definitions to avoid schema issues. If errors persist, create diagnostic scripts to check function signatures, dependencies, and table structures before attempting fixes. Key file: scripts/fix-invitation-function-safe.sql handles these edge cases properly.
- Analytics page legacy Supabase client fix: Fixed analytics page loading issues by removing the legacy `src/lib/supabase.ts` file that was causing "Multiple GoTrueClient instances detected" warnings and conflicts with the modern SSR setup. The analytics page was importing `{ supabase } from '@/lib/supabase'` which created multiple client instances. Solution: 1) Delete the legacy supabase.ts file, 2) Update analytics page to use `createClient()` from '@/lib/supabase/client', 3) Added proper local client creation in checkAuth function, 4) Added master_admin and sub_admin roles to analytics page authorization, 5) Documented fix in lessons learned. Key changes: Replaced global client import with local client creation, each component now calls createClient() when needed, prevents "Multiple GoTrueClient instances detected" warnings, ensures proper SSR compatibility. Result: Analytics page now loads properly with correct authentication handling and no client conflicts.
- Maintenance system implementation: Created comprehensive maintenance task management system with staff assignment and external contractor invitations. Key components: 1) Database migration at supabase/migrations/20250131_create_maintenance_system.sql creates 9 tables including maintenance_tasks, task_assignments, task_contractor_invitations, 2) Server actions in src/app/actions/maintenance.ts handle task CRUD, staff assignment, and contractor invitations with proper organization-based access control, 3) Enhanced MaintenanceTaskModal with tabbed interface for no assignment/internal staff/external contractor options, 4) Integrated with facility/building selection and available staff lookup, 5) Activity logging and RLS policies ensure data isolation, 6) External contractors receive secure invitation tokens valid for 7 days. Implementation pattern: Server actions use createServerSupabaseClient() for auth and getServiceRoleClient() for database operations. UI uses tabs for assignment type selection with dynamic form fields. Always include organization_id for data isolation. Tables use UUID primary keys and proper foreign key relationships. Migration script at scripts/apply-maintenance-migration.js helps with deployment.
- OpenAI dependencies removal: Completely removed OpenAI integration from the application to reduce dependencies and costs. Changes: 1) Removed 'openai' package from package.json and ran npm install to update package-lock.json, 2) Removed OPENAI_API_KEY from .env.local environment variables, 3) Removed OpenAI reference from supabase/config.toml, 4) Updated .cursorrules and .cursor/rules/devinrule.mdc documentation to use Anthropic as default LLM provider, 5) Removed all GPT model references from configuration files. The application now uses Anthropic Claude as the primary LLM provider for any development tools or documentation that reference LLM usage. This change reduces the number of external API dependencies and associated costs.
- Sign-in page LastPass hydration error fix: Fixed hydration error on sign-in page caused by LastPass browser extension injecting DOM elements (data-lastpass-icon-root). Applied the same NoSSR pattern used in sign-up page. Solution: 1) Split SignInPage into SignInForm component, 2) Wrapped SignInForm with NoSSR component that renders client-side only, 3) Added AuthLoadingSkeleton as fallback during SSR, 4) This prevents browser extension DOM modifications from causing hydration mismatches. The pattern maintains SSR benefits while gracefully handling browser extension interference. Key imports: NoSSR from '@/components/ui/no-ssr' and AuthLoadingSkeleton from '@/components/ui/auth-loading-skeleton'.
- Light mode background fix: Fixed hardcoded theme colors that broke light mode compatibility. Key changes: 1) Replaced hardcoded bg-gradient-to-br from-gray-900 via-purple-900/20 to-gray-900 with bg-background, 2) Updated text-white to text-foreground, text-gray-300 to text-foreground, text-gray-400 to text-muted-foreground, 3) Changed bg-gray-800/50 to bg-card/50, border-gray-700 to border-border, 4) Updated purple colors to use primary (bg-purple-600/20 to bg-primary/20, text-purple-400 to text-primary), 5) Fixed form inputs to use bg-input, placeholder-muted-foreground, focus:border-ring, 6) Applied to buildings page and facilities/new page. Rule: Never use hardcoded colors like gray-900, text-white, border-gray-700 - always use semantic CSS variables (bg-background, text-foreground, border-border, etc.) for theme compatibility.
- Field reservation sign-up flow fix: Fixed the flow where guest users submit field reservations and are redirected to sign-up. Implementation: 1) FieldDetailModal saves reservation data to localStorage as `pendingFieldDetailReservation` before showing auth modal, 2) Auth modal displays for 2 seconds with loading spinner then auto-redirects to sign-up page, 3) User dashboard checks for pending reservations in useEffect and auto-submits them after authentication, 4) Shows success toast and clears pending data after successful submission. Key pattern: Save complex form data to localStorage before auth redirect, restore and auto-process after sign-up to prevent data loss. Files: src/components/facility/FieldDetailModal.tsx handles pre-auth saving, src/app/(app)/user-dashboard/page.tsx handles post-auth submission. Documentation in FIELD_RESERVATION_SIGNUP_FIX.md.
- Authentication and sign-up fixes (Feb 2025): Fixed two critical issues: 1) Sign-up page had hardcoded dark theme colors breaking light mode - replaced all with semantic CSS variables (bg-background, text-foreground, etc.), 2) Master admin access issues due to missing three-tier authentication migration - created safe migration script that adds organization support and RLS policies. Key learnings: The users table uses 'role' column not 'user_role', always use semantic CSS variables for theme compatibility, three-tier system requires proper organization assignment for access control.
- Facility detail page loading fix: Fixed facility detail pages showing loading spinner forever when double-clicked from map. Root cause: getFacilityById function in src/app/actions/facilities.ts was using .eq('id', user.id) for user profile lookup instead of .eq('email', user.email). The users table structure uses email as the lookup key, not the auth user ID. Fixed by changing line 181 to use email lookup, added fallback logic for master admin, and enhanced error logging. Also created getBuildingsByFacilityId server action to replace client-side BuildingService calls which lacked proper authentication. Key lesson: Always use email for user profile lookups in server actions, not the auth user ID. Use server actions instead of client services for authenticated data fetching.

